<head>
   <title>Success Stories</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000" background="027.jpg">

<h2><a href="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov"><img src="/rsc/photow8.gif" alt="= CESD Home Page ="  align=left></a><a href="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov/ss/index.html"><img src="success.gif" border=2 height=44 width=160 align=left></a><font SIZE=-1><a href="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov/success.html">Renew
America Success Stories</a></font></h2><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>

<p>
<hr width="100%" ></p>

<h2>Oregon Resource Efficient Communities</h2>

<address>Contact:</address>

<address>Mr. Gary Curtis, Technical Specialist</address>

<address>Oregon Department of Energy</address>

<address>625 Marion St., NE</address>

<address>Salem, OR 97310</address>

<address>tel: (503) 378-8446</address>

<address>fax: (503) 373-7806</address>

<address>No Internet Link Currently Available</address>

<address>
<br CLEAR="all"><img src="mrule.gif" alt=" " border=0 height=5 width=640></address>

<p><b><font SIZE=+2>Description</font></b></p>

<p>The Oregon Resource Efficient Communities (OREC) program is a state-sponsored,
community-based effort to improve the resource and energy efficiency of
local businesses, schools and government through program and management
analyses and energy audits. Businesses participating in the program can
expect to save energy, conserve water, reduce solid wastes and increase
recycling rates, thereby saving money and increasing productivity.</p>

<p>While garbage, water and energy prices in the Northwest have long been
among the lowest in the nation, dwindling natural resources and rising
environmental costs mean that Oregon businesses and public agencies must
be energy-conscious to be competitive. The OREC program was developed to
anticipate this change and to help to secure a healthy economy and healthy
environment for Oregon's future.</p>

<p>The River City Resource Group (RCRG), a resource efficiency consultant
under contract with the State, has been hired to perform comprehensive
resource efficiency audits on participating businesses and to identify
resource efficiency opportunities and goals. The Departments of Energy
and Environmental Quality staff will then recommend specific measures to
achieve these goals, and will estimate the costs and projected savings
of such measures. Sample measures include capital improvements such as
lighting retrofits and operation modifications such as waste prevention.</p>

<p>Participation in the program is voluntary. Similar efforts in other
states have shown that a community-wide approach to resource efficiency
is more successful than business-by-business control and regulation. The
project began in 1994 in Corvallis and will remain a pilot project there
until 1997. At that time, it is expected that the program will be expanded
to five more Oregon communities.</p>

<p>The program offers direct savings in energy, water and waste disposal
costs. The program also provides participants with a competitive edge,
as they reduce costs and receive productivity gains through process improvements.
The knowledge shared promotes long-term economic sustainability and will
attract new businesses to Oregon.</p>

<p>&quot;This is one of those win-win situations,&quot; says Jeff Demetrescu,
executive director of the Corvallis Area Chamber of Commerce. &quot;It's
good for business, and it's good for the environment.&quot;</p>

<center><p><img src="mrule.gif" alt=" " border=0 height=5 width=640></p></center>

<p><b><font SIZE=+2>Program Highlights</font></b></p>

<p><b><font SIZE=+1>Participants</font></b></p>

<ul>
<li>Nine Corvallis organizations have volunteered to participate in the
program, including a produce grower and processor, an insurance agency,
a credit union, a hardware store, the school district, the public works
department, a construction company and a fiberboard manufacturer.</li>

<li>Each participant has agreed to implement at least three of the recommended
modifications.</li>

<li>It is hoped that participants will communicate with each other and
help businesses enroll in the program and implement efficiency efforts.</li>
</ul>

<p><b><font SIZE=+1>Program Details</font></b></p>

<ul>
<li>Recommended capital improvements have included installing fluorescent
lighting, purchasing recycling containers and installing energy management
systems.</li>

<li>Recommended changes in operations and management practices have included
turning off lights, setting back thermostats, revising packaging and recycling.</li>

<li>The Corvallis Chamber of Commerce has agreed to support a resource
conservation manager (RCM), who will establish an energy accounting system,
identify efficiency opportunities, implement conservation measures and
track savings. It is expected that energy savings will pay the cost of
the RCM.</li>
</ul>

<p><b><font SIZE=+1>Financing</font></b></p>

<ul>
<li>The Oregon Energy Department's Small Scale Energy Loan program will
finance most measures, and many businesses qualify for the state's 35%
Business Energy Tax Credit.</li>
</ul>

<center><p><img src="mrule.gif" alt=" " border=0 height=5 width=640></p></center>

<dl>
<p><b><font SIZE=+2>Vital Statistics</font></b></p>

<p><img src="mball.gif" alt="*" hspace=3 vspace=2 border=0 height=9 width=9><b>Program
Management/Partnerships: </b>The Oregon Resource Efficient Communities
program is managed by the Oregon Department of Energy. Partnerships have
been developed with, among other organizations and agencies, the Department
of Environmental Quality, the River City Resource Group (RCRG) and the
Corvallis Chamber of Commerce.</p>

<p><img src="mball.gif" alt="*" hspace=3 vspace=2 border=0 height=9 width=9><b>Budget:</b>
The latest figures are available by contacting the program.</p>

<p><img src="mball.gif" alt="*" hspace=3 vspace=2 border=0 height=9 width=9><b>Community
Served: </b>The 45,000 residents of Corvallis, Oregon. It is expected that
this program will eventually be expanded to serve the majority of Oregon
residents.</p>

<p><img src="mball.gif" alt="*" hspace=3 vspace=2 border=0 height=9 width=9><b>Measures
of Success:</b></p>

<dl>
<dl>
<li>The program's benefits will be measured by savings in energy, water
and waste disposal costs. Increased productivity from process improvements
will also be measured. These benefits can be passed on to consumers in
lower product costs and to employees in benefit and pay increases.</li>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>

<dl>
<p><img src="mball.gif" alt="*" hspace=3 vspace=2 border=0 height=9 width=9><b>Contact</b>:</p>
</dl>

<dl>
<dl>
<address>Mr. Gary Curtis, Technical Specialist</address>

<address>Oregon Department of Energy</address>

<address>625 Marion St., NE</address>

<address>Salem, OR 97310</address>

<address>tel: (503) 378-8446</address>

<address>fax: (503) 373-7806</address>

<address>No Internet Link Currently Available</address>
</dl>
</dl>

<p><img src="mrule.gif" alt=" " border=0 height=5 width=640>
<br><i><font SIZE=-2>Success stories designed by Mark Nowak</font></i></p>

<p><a href="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov/index.html"><img src="left_arr.gif" border=2 height=56 width=72 align=bottom></a></p>

<p><i><a href="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov/comment-form.shtml">Comments
&amp; Questions</a></i><b> | </b><i><a href="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov/suggest.shtml">Suggest
a Resource</a></i> </p>

</body>
