<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Rural</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF><A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A><A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt="= Slide Shows =""></a><p><b><a href="/slides/rural/index.html">Act Locally Slide Show</a></b><br><i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p><center><a href="l/74.gif"><img src="t/74.gif"></a></center><p><!--**head**--> In addition to protecting fragile shorelines from erosion, the tree cribs also provide wildlife habitat. Waterfowl use the cribs for nesting. A professor at Louisiana State University first suggested the use of this type of shoreline fence, an erosion-control intervention he'd seen employed in the Netherlands. <p>The Jefferson Parish project offers one classic "sustainable" example of converting a nuisance waste into a resource.This presentation has offered an array of examples of "sustainable community" projects throughout the country, describing the "where," the "what," and the "why." But questions may remain about how these communities have managed such accomplishments.<!--**foot**--><p><a href = "73.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a><a href = "/slides/rural/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a><a href = "75.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><address><p><a href="/rsc/comment-form.shtml">Comments &amp; Questions</a></i><b> | </b><i><a href="/rsc/suggest.shtml">Suggest a Resource</a></i></address><h5>URL: http://<a href="http://solstice.crest.org/">solstice.crest.org</a>/<a href="/">doe</a>/<a href="/">sustainable</a>/<a href="/slideshows/">slideshows</a>/<a href="/slides/rural">rural</a>/74.html</h5></body></html>
