<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Rural</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF><A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A><A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt="= Slide Shows =""></a><p><b><a href="/slides/rural/index.html">Act Locally Slide Show</a></b><br><i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p><center><a href="l/36.gif"><img src="t/36.gif"></a><p></center><!--**head**--><I>"A natural disaster is often two calamities rolled into one.The first is the loss of life and property. The second is the failure of disaster victims and their communities to capture the enormous opportunities offered by reconstruction."</I><br>- from "The Case for Sustainable Redevelopment" by William S. Becker of the U.S. Department of Energy<p>In the past, communities have tried to re-build in the path of disaster; now communities are recreating their relationship with rivers in places like Pattonsburg, Missouri, and Soldiers Grove, Wisconsin.<p>They are turning unsustainable communities into sustainable communities. <!--**foot**--><p><a href = "35.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a><a href = "/slides/rural/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a><a href = "37.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><address><p><a href="/rsc/comment-form.shtml">Comments &amp; Questions</a></i><b> | </b><i><a href="/rsc/suggest.shtml">Suggest a Resource</a></i></address><h5>URL: http://<a href="http://solstice.crest.org/">solstice.crest.org</a>/<a href="/">doe</a>/<a href="/">sustainable</a>/<a href="/slideshows/">slideshows</a>/<a href="/slides/rural">rural</a>/36.html</h5></body></html>
