<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Rural</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF><A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A><A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt="= Slide Shows =""></a><p><b><a href="/slides/rural/index.html">Act Locally Slide Show</a></b><br><i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p><center><a href="l/04.gif"><img src="t/04.gif"></a></center><p><!--**head**--> And then, at the continuum's other end, there are those once-thriving small towns and villages that fail to attract now even their own. They are peopled by the elderly, who watch the town's young move away, who witness their town's sad decay, who watch their Main Street merchants sell out, close down, hammer up sheets of plywood.Residents of rural areas, people who are often more attuned than their urban counterparts to finite resources, both human and natural,  have started to recognize the threats. And they've begun to act, relying upon the principles and techniques of sustainability and sustainable development.<!--**foot**--><p><a href = "3.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a><a href = "/slides/rural/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a><a href = "5.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><address><p><a href="/rsc/comment-form.shtml">Comments &amp; Questions</a></i><b> | </b><i><a href="/rsc/suggest.shtml">Suggest a Resource</a></i></address>

