<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Rural</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF><A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A><A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt="= Slide Shows =""></a><p><b><a href="/slides/rural/index.html">Act Locally Slide Show</a></b><br><i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p><center><a href="l/68.gif"><img src="t/68.gif"></a></center><p><!--**head**--> Beginning in 1987, a committee initiated a study of how to promote enjoyment of the Edisto River while also protecting and preserving it. The Canoe and Kayak Trail emerged from their work, as did the annual Edisto Riverfest.The trail, its guided canoe trips, and the Riverfest have attracted regional and national attention and have provided a sustainable economic boost to the community of Walterboro. Tourism has increased and trail-related jobs have been created.Initial funding for the trail included $10,000 appropriated by Colleton County for purchasing canoes and $2,500 from the South Carolina Department of Parks, Recreation and Tourism for brochures. Today, the Edisto Canoe and Kayak Trail Commission is self-supporting.<!--**foot**--><p><a href = "67.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a><a href = "/slides/rural/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a><a href = "69.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><address><p><a href="/rsc/comment-form.shtml">Comments &amp; Questions</a></i><b> | </b><i><a href="/rsc/suggest.shtml">Suggest a Resource</a></i></address>

