<head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Rural</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF><A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A><A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt="= Slide Shows =""></a><p><b><a href="/slides/rural/index.html">Act Locally Slide Show</a></b><br><i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p><center><a href="l/19.gif"><img src="t/19.gif"></a></center><p><!--**head**-->"Houses, neighborhoods, workplaces, shopping centers, schools, transportation systems, and public buildings are all cash cows waiting to be milked."	- From "Community Energy Workbook," Rocky Mountain Institute. By cutting their energy expenses, residents of rural America end up with dollars to spend elsewhere. On schools, for example, purchasing books and paying teachers instead of paying through the nose for inefficient lighting or for heat that escapes through single-pane windows and uninsulated walls. 	Such energy costs received considerable attention when the residents of Soldiers Grove, Wisconsin, decided to build a brand new town.<!--**foot**--><p><a href = "18.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a><a href = "/slides/rural/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a><a href = "20.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><address><p><a href="/rsc/comment-form.shtml">Comments &amp; Questions</a></i><b> | </b><i><a href="/rsc/suggest.shtml">Suggest a Resource</a></i></address></body></html>
