<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Urban</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= CESD Home Page ="></A>
<A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt = "= Slide Shows ="></a>
<p>

<b><a href="/slideshows/urban/index.html">Sustainable Development Slideshow</a></b><br>
<i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i>


<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<center><a href="l/17.gif"><img src="t/17.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<!--**head**-->



 	The city of Chattanooga found just such a "fish head" on the shores of the Tennessee River. In 1978, state officials in Tennessee closed the Walnut Street Bridge. The bridge, built in 1891 in Chattanooga to span the Tennessee River, was a safety hazard, and demolition loomed.
<P>
But a group of citizens rallied to save the bridge. They argued it could enliven a new riverfront park development. Funds, public and private, were raised. The bridge was saved, restored, rehabilitated.
<p>
Completed in 1993, the Walnut Street Bridge has promoted natural resource conservation, economic progress and human development...The bridge is said to be a source of inspiration and satisfaction for the citizens of Chattanooga.
<p>
The bridge helped resurrect the city's abandoned and under-used riverfront. Project supervisors report that runners, walkers, cyclists, roller-bladers, and pedestrian commuters have now reclaimed this once languishing area. The bridge has helped link Chattanooga's North Shore business district, its central downtown business and entertainment district, as well as its Bluff View cultural and historic district.


<!--**foot**--><p>
<a href = "16.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a>
<a href = "/slideshows/urban/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a>
<a href = "18.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a>
<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
