<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Urban</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= CESD Home Page ="></A>
<A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt = "= Slide Shows ="></a>
<p>

<b><a href="/slideshows/urban/index.html">Sustainable Development Slideshow</a></b><br>
<i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i>


<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<center><a href="l/30.gif"><img src="t/30.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<!--**head**-->



 Most of the river's bridges "accommodate bicycles, pedestrians and the 
 disabled either grudgingly or not at all," Browning wrote. "Thousands of 
 people living within sight of their high-rise offices are too intimidated 
 by the gauntlet of bridge crossing to ride a bicycle or walk to work."
<p>
 Grassroots groups convinced local and state agencies to examine how Portland's
bridges might better serve its resident walkers and wheelers and bicyclists. A
task force spent 18 months identifying problems and proposing solutions. Some
gains have been made. The Burnside Bridge now features bicycle lanes. But more
work remains.
<p>
Browning suggests urban designers must "plan transportation systems that allow
human beings to go confidently wherever they please, under their own power and at
their own pace."

<!--**foot**--><p>
<a href = "29.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a>
<a href = "/slideshows/urban/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a>
<a href = "32.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a>
