<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Rural</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF><A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A><A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt="= Slide Shows =""></a><p><b><a href="/slides/rural/index.html">Act Locally Slide Show</a></b><br><i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p><center><a href="l/59.gif"><img src="t/59.gif"></a></center><p><!--**head**--> The town worked with students from the University of Wisconsin to inventory Dunn's natural and cultural resources. The inventory detailed wetlands, watersheds, and wildlife habitat areas. It described historic sites, woodlots, and prime agricultural land. According to the town's own description, the inventory "increased local awareness of the value of agricultural land, natural environmental resources, and the very strong interrelations between the physical, natural and cultural characteristics in the town."	Such increased awareness garnered local support for preservation efforts.The Land Use Program reportedly "has brought about an increased sense of community in the town and elevated the public's awareness that the natural, economic and human interactions together form Dunn's ecosystem." The town's efforts have been celebrated nationally - by Renew America and others. Claudine Schneider, chair of Renew America, has said, "When it comes to environmental achievement, the Town of Dunn and their land use plan and open space preservation program represent the very best our country has to offer."<!--**foot**--><p><a href = "58.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a><a href = "/slides/rural/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a><a href = "60.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><address><p><a href=