<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Urban</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= CESD Home Page ="></A>
<A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt = "= Slide Shows ="></a>
<p>

<b><a href="/slideshows/urban/index.html">Sustainable Development Slideshow</a></b><br>
<i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i>


<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<center><a href="l/66.gif"><img src="t/66.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<!--**head**-->
	Across the Hudson, similar efforts are under way in Newark, New Jersey, home base for Rutgers Urban Gardening, which also serves Orange, East Orange, and Irvington.
<p>
Through the Rutgers Urban Gardening program, a state and federally-funded project of Rutgers University Cooperative Extension, more than 300 vacant lots have been transformed. Trashed and desolate spaces like this one on Lincoln Avenue in Newark have been converted into 2,000 lively and productive neighborhood gardens.


