<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Rural</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF><A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A><A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt="= Slide Shows 
=""></a><p><b><a href="/slides/rural/index.html">Act Locally Slide Show</a></b><br><i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i><p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p><center><a href="l/11.gif"><img src="t/11.gif"></a></center><p><!--**head**-->	
This presentation highlights how several rural communities are incorporating this concept into their development efforts. We begin in rural Virginia. It seems fitting that in Thomas Jefferson's own backyard people have begun to embrace the principles of "
sustainability."	In the rolling Virginia foothills just west of Charlottesville. Architect William A. Edgerton has designed a residential community based upon the innovative concepts of "open space development."<!--**foot**--><p><a href = "10.
html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a><a href = "/slides/rural/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a><a href = "12.html"><img src="http://
