<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Urban</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= CESD Home Page ="></A>
<A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt = "= Slide Shows ="></a>
<p>

<b><a href="/slideshows/urban/index.html">Sustainable Development Slideshow</a></b><br>
<i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i>


<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<center><a href="l/56.gif"><img src="t/56.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<!--**head**-->

More than two thousand miles away, in a very different climate, builders have been enlisted also in sustainable efforts in Austin, Texas.
<P>
 Austin's "Green Builder Program" has received support from diverse sources. From the U.S. Department of Energy. From Habitat for Humanity. From the local builders association...
<p>
As originally conceived, the Green Builder Program was designed to expand an existing system of criteria used to rate the energy efficiency of new homes. Its newer criteria were developed to consider issues related to water use, building materials, and solid waste.
<p>
Pictured here is a newly-constructed residence employing passive design, recycled and salvaged materials, rainwater collection, efficient lighting and appliances and other "green" features.


