<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Urban</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= CESD Home Page ="></A>
<A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt = "= Slide Shows ="></a>
<p>

<b><a href="/slideshows/urban/index.html">Sustainable Development Slideshow</a></b><br>
<i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i>


<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<center><a href="l/65.gif"><img src="t/65.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<!--**head**-->
 	On the East coast, other gardening projects enliven and enrich urban areas.
<p>
In 1994, volunteers from the "Green Guerillas" group in New York City provided, free-of-charge, nearly $300,000 in plants, gardening materials, and hands-on assistance to more than 20,000 New Yorkers.
<p>
The Green Guerillas volunteer their assistance to community gardens, housing shelters, and institutions. They inform urban residents and city officials about how community gardening can strengthen low-income neighborhoods.


