<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Urban</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= CESD Home Page ="></A>
<A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt = "= Slide Shows ="></a>
<p>

<b><a href="/slideshows/urban/index.html">Sustainable Development Slideshow</a></b><br>
<i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i>


<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<center><a href="l/76.gif"><img src="t/76.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<!--**head**-->

<I>"Achieving sustainable cities requires active citizen
participation...sustainability requires inspiring citizens to move from
short-term, selfish interests toward a broader long-term public good: active
responsibility."</I> 	<br>
- Randolph T. Hester Jr., from "Life, Liberty, and the Pursuit of Sustainable Happiness," in Places, winter 1995
<p>
	 One lesson, perhaps the most important, is that sustainable development must be a community-wide, grass-roots commitment. Citizens must be involved.
<p>
When Americans are inspired (as during World War II)  and educated, rather than pushed, they often embrace efficient use of resources.


<!--**foot**--><p>
<a href = "75.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a>
