<i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i>


<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<center><a href="l/16.gif"><img src="t/16.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<!--**head**-->



	Randolph T. Hester Jr., a professor of landscape architecture at the University of California, Berkeley, bemoans such waste. He writes about "finding fish heads." 
<p>
In years past, fish were caught, cleaned, cut into fillets. Fish heads were considered useless waste. Today, fish heads have new value as organic fertilizer and other products. Hester, using a metaphor, encourages city officials to search out these so-called "fish heads" in their own communities - old and neglected buildings - like these in Atlanta; untapped energy sources; waste heat that can be captured; retired residents whose life experiences can offer invaluable resources; and trash that can be recycled...


<!--**foot**--><p>
<a href = "15.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a>
<a href = "/slideshows/urban/index.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/toc_button.gif" alt = "=Table of Content="></a>
<a href = "17.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/next_button.gif" alt = "=Next="></a>
<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<address>
<p>
<a href="/rsc/comment-form.shtml">Comments &amp; Questions</a></i><b> | </b><i><a href="/rsc/suggest.shtml">Suggest a Resource</a></i></address>


</body></html>
