<html><head><title>CESD: Slide Shows: Urban</title></head><body BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>

<A HREF="/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/ncsdicon.gif" ALT="= CESD Home Page ="></A>
<A HREF="/slideshows/"><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/bugs/slides.gif" alt = "= Slide Shows ="></a>
<p>

<b><a href="/slideshows/urban/index.html">Sustainable Development Slideshow</a></b><br>
<i>National Center for Appropriate Technology</i>


<p><img SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><p>
<center><a href="l/28.gif"><img src="t/28.gif"></a></center>
<p>

<!--**head**-->



 In his book Babbitt, author Sinclair Lewis informed us that George Babbitt's car was "poetry, tragedy, love and heroism." 

For many city planners and urban residents, gasoline-driven cars, trucks and buses are more tragic than poetic, polluting the air, requiring the use of precious space for parking,  and consuming incalculable resources.


<!--**foot**--><p>
<a href = "27.html"><img src="http://solstice.crest.org/common/prev_button.gif" alt = "=Previous="></a>
