<A HREF="guru_dir/guru.html"><IMG ALIGN="Middle" SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_guru.gif" ALT="The Movie Guru Review of the Week" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1" VSPACE="3"></A>

<P>
<IMG SRC="graphics_dir/psychic.gif" ALT="Psychic Movie Predictions" HEIGHT=149 WIDTH=180 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=RIGHT>


<H3>Evita (PG)</H3>
Starring in the title role "she was born to play," Madonna recasts herself as Serious Thespian in this adaptation of Andrew Lloyd Webber's pop musical Evita. She plays the strong-willed wife of an Argentinean dictator who inspires her country.
<BR<STRONG>>Prediction:</STRONG> Madonna will present her most dramatic facial expressions ever--but, alas, we'll have to watch them for more than the usual five minute video length. 
<BR><STRONG>Probable Entertainment Value: E</STRONG>

<H3>First Strike (PG-13)</H3>
Jackie Chan is back! This time, the world's most lovable karate ass-kicker plays a Hong Kong policeman who hits the road in search of a nuclear warhead. Somehow, he finds himself working for both the CIA and Russian intelligence. That Jackie!
<BR><STRONG>Prediction:</STRONG>  Despite his amiable demeanor, Jackie will be forced to teach a few thugs some important lessons in humility. He'll also do lots of leaping and running. Then critics will hail this as "Jackie's best movie ever!"
<BR><STRONG>Probable Entertainment Value: A</STRONG>

<TABLE BORDER CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=50%>
<TR><TD><STRONG>ENTERTAINMENT VALUE TABLE</STRONG><BR><STRONG>A:</STRONG> Pay full price for an evening show. <BR><STRONG>B:</STRONG> Hit a matinee. <BR><STRONG>C:</STRONG> Wait until it's out on video. <BR><STRONG>D:</STRONG> Looks like dollar theater material. <BR><STRONG>E:</STRONG> A late night cable movie, at best. <BR><STRONG>F:</STRONG> The network TV premiere is four years away. Wait it out.</TD></TR></TABLE>

<H3>The People vs. Larry Flynt (R)</H3>
Larry Flynt: Defender of free speech or scumball pornographer? The answer is both in this bio-pic of America's most infamous magazine publisher. Directed by Milos Foreman (One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest), it covers the creation of Flynt's porn empire with Hustler and on to his court battles over free speech. 
<BR><STRONG>Prediction:</STRONG> Woody Harrelson has at long last found the role most appropriate for his talents--and Foreman will use them well to tell an amazing, distinctly American tale.
<BR><STRONG>Probable Entertainment Value: A</STRONG>

<H3>The Relic (R)</H3>
The title character is a fearsome creature that lurks in the basement of a natural history museum and kills people in a gruesome manner. Penelope Ann Miller stars as the evolutionary biologist hot on its tail, along with Tom Sizemore as a tough police lieutenant. 
<BR><STRONG>Prediction:</STRONG> After killing scads of idiotic people, the creature will be pursued through dark, confining spaces--like tunnels or vents or something--and eventually be blown to smithereens. But will it really die?
<BR><STRONG>Probable Entertainment Value: C</STRONG>

<H3>Small Wonders (G)</H3>
Nominated for Best Documentary Feature by the Academy in 1995, Small Wonders tells the true story of a single mother who moved to East Harlem and began teaching violin to support her family. When her position got eliminated due to budget cuts, she started her own non-profit organization in 1990 to fund a violin program for three East Harlem public schools. 
<BR><STRONG>Prediction:</STRONG> In the mood to renew your faith in public education? This is the documentary for you.
<BR><STRONG>Probable Entertainment Value: B</STRONG>

<H3>Turbulence (R)</H3>
Ray Liotta plays a serial killer who takes control of an airplane flying through severe weather after four Federal marshalls and both pilots are killed. He then chases after Lauren Holly's resilient flight attendant as they engage in a psychological battle of wills.
<BR><STRONG>Prediction:</STRONG> Hmmm, let's see--two hours on an airplane with a psycho killer at 36,000 feet while Lauren Holly screams...sounds like the entertainment opportunity of a lifetime! How can it possibly miss?
<BR><STRONG>Probable Entertainment Value: D</STRONG>


<P><HR>
<IMG SRC="graphics_dir/video_gogo.gif" ALT="Videos a Go-Go" HEIGHT=85 WIDTH=180 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>

I've always liked winter better in movies than in real life, especially snow. On film, you can enjoy the serenity of the season without wiping off windshields or slogging through slush. And there's no danger of losing body parts through overexposure.
<P>So this week's video picks are a salute to snow, for people who like the idea of winter more than the reality (next week, we'll do a tropical theme for those of you who just want to forget that it's January).
<P>A lot of people called <STRONG>Fargo</STRONG> the best movie of 1996. It's also the best winter movie I can remember. Northern Minnesota isn't just the setting for Joel and Ethan Coen's morbid, hilarious comedy--it's a frozen, monolithic presence, throwing the movie's characters into colorful relief. Frances McDormand gave the performance of the year as a pregnant police chief unraveling a kidnapping gone wrong, and the rest of the cast is nearly as good. The movie's also a sly send-up of the annoying "based on a true story" genre.
<P>Maybe the most famous winter scenes in any movie are from Charlie Chaplin's <STRONG>The Gold Rush,</STRONG> in which Chaplin's trademark tramp goes prospecting in the Yukon and has to fight off man, beast, and especially Mother Nature. The 1925 silent classic is still fresh and funny 70 years on. If you haven't seen it, what are you waiting for?
<P>If the comic cannibalism in Chaplin's film isn't enough for you, you can see the real thing in 1993's <STRONG>Alive,</STRONG> which recounts the true story of a Uraguayan rugby team stranded in the snowy Andes. The movie has a terrifying plane crash, an equally devastating avalanche scene and undeniable drama. Whether it's something you actually want to submit yourself to is, well, a matter of taste.
<P>The final pick, 1992's overlooked <STRONG>Orlando,</STRONG> isn't specifically a winter movie, but it has one of my favorite winter scenes: a dazzling 17th century ice carnival that sings--as does the whole film--with magic and imagination. Based on Virginia Woolf's tale of a gender-switching immortal (played guilelessly by Tilda Swinton), Orlando manages to compress four centuries of social commentary into a festive, 93-minute romp.

<P><EM>--Jesse Fox Mayshark</EM>

<HR></BODY></HTML>
