<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Metro Pulse Movie Blurbs</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="../../../index.shtml"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../../graphics_misc/b_home.gif" ALT="Front Page" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../../zine.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../../graphics_misc/b_zine.gif" ALT="The 'Zine" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../../suncity.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../../graphics_misc/b_suncity.gif" ALT="Sunsphere City" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../../market.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../../graphics_misc/b_market.gif" ALT=" Marketplace" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../../bonus.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../../graphics_misc/b_bonus.gif" ALT="Bonus Track" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../graphics_dir/hed_guru.gif" ALT="Movie Guru" HEIGHT=27 WIDTH=300><BR>

<A HREF="../menu.html"><IMG ALIGN="Middle" SRC="../../../graphics_misc/b_cinemetro.gif" ALT="Cinemetropolis" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1" VSPACE="3"></A>
<A HREF="../current.html"><IMG ALIGN="Middle" SRC="../../../graphics_misc/b_nowplaying.gif" ALT="Currently Showing" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1" VSPACE="3"></A>
<A HREF="../past_future.html"><IMG ALIGN="Middle" SRC="../../../graphics_misc/b_pastfuture.gif" ALT="Past and Future" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1" VSPACE="3"></A>

<H1><IMG SRC="701_crucible.gif" HEIGHT=144 WIDTH=252 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>The Play's the Thing</H1>
<STRONG>For better and worse, The Crucible is faithful to its source.</STRONG>
<P><EM>by Jesse Fox Mayshark</EM>
<P>There are a lot of reasons to appreciate the new (and first) movie adaptation of Arthur Miller's 1953 play, The Crucible.
<P>The first is simply that the film could not have been made 44 years ago, when the play set audiences and critics buzzing with its daring, explicitly political theme.
<P>And the new production, with a screenplay by Miller himself, is a scrupulously faithful rendering of the Salem witch-hunt drama that will bring smiles to high school English teachers across the nation (in a way that, say, last year's Demi Moore-ized The Scarlet Letter did not).
<P>But that faithfulness also gives a chance to reassess Miller's original work from a distance, and truth be told, it comes up a little short. The movie is meant to canonize the play, to establish it as a masterwork of 20th century drama, and it's only partly successful--despite some terrific acting and crisp direction--because the play just isn't up to it.
<P>The story is familiar, of course. A gaggle of teenage girls in 17th century Salem, Mass., sets off a tempest of Puritan "cleansing" by accusing dozens of people of witchcraft. Miller meant The Crucible, with its demented courtroom scenes and bizarre interrogations, as an indictment of totali- tarianism in general and McCarthy-ism in particular.
<P>All of the play's big points--that fear breeds fear, that innocent people can be compelled to confess, that campaigns for purity are inherently oppressive--still resonate. When one of the judges mutters, "I hadn't expected so much of our evidence to come from children," it's hard not to think of the recent goings-on in Wenatchee, Wash., where dozens of adults were accused of participating in a child sex ring that turned out to be an invention of troubled children and overzealous prosecutors.
<P>Even so, The Crucible is missing something. It's too mannered and didactic to be completely involving as a story, and as a political statement, it seems more studied than passionate. Unlike some political art--Picasso's "Guernica," for example--Miller's play loses impact outside its original context.
<P>The movie (like the play) also fails to capitalize on its other major theme. The girls' accusations are actually triggered by their own experimentations with magic, which the movie shows in a striking opening sequence. Implicit in the fireside ritual--and in the nightmare of injustice that follows--is the teens' rebellion against sexual and social repression. But that gets pushed to the sidelines in The Crucible's film version, a victim of Miller's preoccupation with McCarthy. (For a better, equally dark exploration of the same theme, check out Peter Jackson's compelling Heavenly Creatures.)
<P>All that aside, there's some fine filmmaking in The Crucible. Director Nicholas Hytner shows the same skill for removing staginess from a theatrical adaptation that he did in 1994's The Madness of King George (a better movie because it was a better play). The movie's final shot in particular shows how much a good director can say with the simplest of images.
<P>On the performance front, The Crucible gives us two of moviedom's biggest names--Daniel Day-Lewis and Winona Ryder--in their second costume drama together (the first was The Age of Innocence.) It confirms what we already knew about them: he's one of the great actors of our time; she's not.
<P>Day-Lewis tears into his role as the wrongly accused John Proctor, who is haunted by past sins but unwilling to compromise his principles. With the exception of Denzel Washington, no other contemporary leading man invests so much passion in every part. Along with Joan Allen as his emotionally bruised wife, Day-Lewis brings much-needed heat to the generally chilly production. Ryder, as the chief accuser, is appropriately shrill and venomous, but she never quite escapes the drama-school earnestness that marks all her serious roles. Her problem is not, as her detractors say, that she can't act; it's that her acting is too obvious, connecting on an intellectual rather than emotional level.
<P>The rest of the cast is adequate but unremarkable, except for Paul Scofield, who is genuinely frightening as the piously bloodthirsty head judge.

<TABLE BORDER CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=230 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=5 VSPACE=5><TR><TD>
MOVIE GURU RATING: <STRONG>Meditative</STRONG><P>
<IMG SRC="../graphics_dir/rating_3.gif" ALT="Enlightening" HEIGHT=72 WIDTH=216>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P>So what we have in The Crucible is not a play or film for the ages, but a well executed, intelligent drama that probably needed to be made, if just as a reminder that we have the freedom to make it. And it's destined for immortality of a sort, I suppose, in the VCRs of high school English classrooms everywhere.



<HR>
</BODY></HTML>
