<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Ear to the Ground</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000"><P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.shtml"><IMG ALIGN=Middle  SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_home.gif" ALT="Staff Directory" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A> <A HREF="../../zine.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_zine.gif" ALT="The 'Zine" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../suncity.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_suncity.gif" ALT="Sunsphere City" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A> <A HREF="../../market.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_market.gif" ALT=" Marketplace" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A> <A HREF="../../bonus.html">
<IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_bonus.gif" ALT="Bonus Track" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="subhead_ear.gif" WIDTH="300" HEIGHT="27" ALT="Ear to the Ground">

<H3>Attention, Frank Cagle. Here's Something That's Not Jimmy Naifeh's Fault</H3>
Remember all the talk in November about how we need to clean up the election commission, put people on there who will do the right thing instead of just treating the seat like a political pay-off? If Republican state Reps. <STRONG>Jim Boyer</STRONG> and <STRONG>H.E. Bittle </STRONG>have their way, Republicans will vote to put a Boyer crony, <STRONG>John Tindell,</STRONG> on the Election Commission. Tindell, a political wannabe who has been unsuccessful in getting himself elected, is a salesman who works out of Hamblen County.
<P>Boyer, the current Knox County delegation chairman, and Bittle, who wants to be delegation chairman, have cut a deal--Boyer gives up the chairmanship, Bittle votes for Tindell to replace the late <STRONG>Hazel Showalter,</STRONG> who was the only woman on the board. They've evidently got the vote of Oak Ridger <STRONG>Randy McNally,</STRONG> who allegedly represents a little slice of northwest Knox County, and they're lobbying for delegation dean <STRONG>Ben Atchley</STRONG>'s vote, which will get them over the top for Tindell.
<P>Sort of affirmative action for white guys.
<P>Left behind in the good ol' boys' tobacco juice are two GOP women, <STRONG>Donna Wright</STRONG> and <STRONG>Becky Longmire, </STRONG>who have been targeted by a smear campaign: "Horrible, horrible. She was for metro. She was for Clinton."
<P>Democrat <STRONG>Joe Armstrong</STRONG> could figure into the mix, too. Could be he'll vote for Bittle for chairman. And since Armstrong has been looking to protect the job of Registrar-at-large <STRONG>Irene Lovely,</STRONG> wonder what Tindell's position will be on the issue of whether Lovely, who bollixed up the unification vote, should keep her job?
<P>But wait. What's that on the horizon?
<P>Looks like <STRONG>Tim Burchett.</STRONG> Looks like Tim Burchett might like to be chairman. Looks like Tim Burchett might think it's time to appoint an educated, hard-nosed woman to the board. Also looks like the redoubtable <STRONG>Mary Lou Horner</STRONG> is riding in with the Women's Political Caucus, reminding the fellas that it might not look good to have a he-man woman-hater board. Saturday morning's meeting of the legislative delegation could get interesting. Be there to see your government at work.

<H3>A River Runs Through It</H3>
Pigeon River fighter <STRONG>Bobby Seay</STRONG> has issued a challenge to Knoxville City Councilman <STRONG>Gary Underwood,</STRONG> who has issued a challenge to Champion International to clean up the Pigeon River, because it runs into the French Broad which runs into the Tennessee which runs through Underwood's district, don'tcha know. Seay, of Newport, is a founding member of the Dead Pigeon River Council, which long has been in the trenches against the North Carolina mega-polluter. He was here the night City Council passed Underwood's resolution, which deplores the pollution of the Pigeon. In a televised interview, Seay asked Underwood to lobby Chattanooga's City Council to pass a similar resolution, since the river runs through there, too. 

<H3>Have Yourself a Merry Little Christmas</H3>
It was the day before Christmas, and <STRONG>Kristin Hoke</STRONG> (a perennial favorite with Metro Pulse  readers) was working out her notice. She'd been informed by Channel 10 news director <STRONG>Margie Nichols</STRONG> that her contract, which was to run out Dec. 31, wouldn't be renewed, and Hoke was slated to work until the following Sunday.
<P>But Nichols ordered Hoke into the personnel office and informed her that that day  would be her last...
<P>A source says "Kristin mentioned that Margie said she was doing this so Kristin could spend time with family and 'enjoy the holidays.' I assume Kristin spent the holidays alone, because her family is nine hours away...This was a calculated move so Kristin couldn't say good-bye to her co-workers and viewers..."
<P>So Hoke started packing her gear. After a few minutes, Nichols walked up to her told her to be out of the building by noon.
<P>"She said 'Let's wrap this up.' Kristin asked if she could stay an hour extra to save some video and Margie said no. We were all in shock..."
<P>Nichols, however, sees it differently: "I didn't fire her on Christmas Eve," she says. "She knew 60 days out [that she didn't have a job after Dec. 31]. I just wanted her to have the holidays off."
<P>Channel 10 has been hemorrhaging employees--55 since last May, sources say.

<H3>Recklessness</H3>
That fatal van-motorcycle accident involving state <STRONG>Sen. Carl Koella</STRONG> caught the attention of the editors of at least one national magazine: American Motorcyclist. In the January issue, a two-page feature about the tragedy, illustrated with a photo of late motorcyclist <STRONG>Terry Barnard's</STRONG> mangled Yamaha, is sardonically headlined "SPIN DOCTRINE: Motorcyclist dies, senator re-elected." The article questions why Koella waited an hour to give a confused account of the accident, and why police waited almost five hours to administer a breath test--but saves its bitterest comments to respond to Koella attorney <STRONG>Jerry Cunningham's</STRONG> pre-election public statements that a mysterious unidentified witness had earlier seen the victim--a 52-year-old churchgoing Navy veteran and head of an Ohio household--driving recklessly. "Could the spin doctors find a way to blame Barnard's death on Barnard himself?" the article goes. "After all, he's only a motorcyclist. And there's an election to be won."

<H3>Moon Over Knoxville</H3>
The rumors of the demise of <STRONG>Blue Moon Bakery</STRONG> were greatly exaggerated. True, the Moon did close for a few days, but it has reopened under new management. Owners <STRONG>Karl</STRONG> and <STRONG>Gloria Testerman</STRONG> handed over the operational reins to partners <STRONG>Kelly Langthim</STRONG> and <STRONG>Pam Watson,</STRONG> who say they've totally revamped the menu and are making the place "bigger, better, friendlier and more service-oriented." The Moon continues to shine Monday through Thursday 8 to 4; Friday and Saturday 8 a.m. to 11 p.m.

<P><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="icon_ear.gif" WIDTH="126" HEIGHT="67" HSPACE="10"><HR>
