<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Eye on the Scene</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000"><P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="../../index.shtml"><IMG ALIGN=Middle  SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_home.gif" ALT="Staff Directory" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A> <A HREF="../../zine.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_zine.gif" ALT="The 'Zine" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A> <A HREF="../../suncity.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_suncity.gif" ALT="Sunsphere City" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A> <A HREF="../../market.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_market.gif" ALT=" Marketplace" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A> <A HREF="../../bonus.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_bonus.gif" ALT="Bonus Track" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="subhead_eye.gif" WIDTH="300" HEIGHT="27" ALT="Eye on the Scene">

<H3>NEW SCHTUFF</H3>
Our very own <STRONG>State Champs</STRONG> are ready and raring to unleash Songs for a Better Tomorrow, their much anticipated nonconcept album. Look for this tour de force at local stores very, very soon, or pick up a copy at the band's CD release party at Mercury Theatre on Friday, January 17.
<P>Those ever-so-clever pranksters the <STRONG>Opposable Thumbs</STRONG> have released Our Cheapest Chicken, a cassette collection of "pisstakes, retakes, remakes, etc., recorded directly on to cassette from a CD master," according to guitarist/singer/musical action hero <STRONG>Todd Steed.</STRONG> Songs include "Superdrag Groupies," "No More Credit at the Liquor Store," and a re-working of the Smokin' Dave smash hit "Truth About Lies." Find it at all your favorite local record outlets.
<P>Also hitting store shelves this week is a sizzling slab of vinyl from technophiles the <STRONG>Speed Freeks.</STRONG> A remixed version of the song "Slower," from the band's Himalayan EP, is backed with "Wise Up," a preview cut from their forthcoming full-length 44.1. Look for that disc sometime in March.
<P>"Rough punk rockers" the <STRONG>Malignmen</STRONG> can also be heard on vinyl, in the form of the seven-inch single "See I Ate," b/w "Bond." Look for a review in this space very soon.
<P>Meanwhile, you'll only be able to find the latest release from local jazz guru <STRONG>Donald Brown</STRONG> in the import bins. Piano Short Stories was released last year for European distribution.

<H3>NEW SCHTUFF, PART DEUX</H3>
On the new band front, local punk, uh, denizens <STRONG>David Burns</STRONG> and <STRONG>Steve Schmidt </STRONG>(of <STRONG>Thumbnail</STRONG> fame, natch) have joined with guitarist <STRONG>Kim Keeler</STRONG> to form the charismatic <STRONG>Kissing Virus.</STRONG> Check out the intoxicating slide guitar action and Keeler's wild and sultry howl (kinda like a hybrid of Thalia Zedek and P.J. Harvey) when they take Gryphon's on Saturday, January 25.
<P><STRONG>Boy Genius</STRONG> features the high energy talents of former FaceDown man <STRONG>Tom Appleton</STRONG> (on guitar), plus bassist <STRONG>Scott West </STRONG>and drummer <STRONG>Dustin West.</STRONG> They recently revealed their punky power poppy nuggets at a show at Mercury Theatre with <STRONG>Torture Kitty;</STRONG> check the Metro Pulse calendar for upcoming dates.
<P>And from the gone-but-definitely-not-forgotten ashes of <STRONG>Wateva </STRONG>comes the bass-and-drums combo <STRONG>40 Deuce.</STRONG> I haven't seen or heard them yet, but trust me: when I do, you'll be the first to know.

<H3>FREEBIE JEEBIES</H3>
No catch, they promise... <STRONG>Cornerstone Recording Studio</STRONG> (yes, right here in Knoxville) is looking to give away ten free recording sessions. To be eligible, you must 1) be an "established musical group with some original material," and 2) send 'em a tape. Cornerstone's <STRONG>Roger White</STRONG> says, "We will listen to all entries, and if we like what we hear, your group will get a free recording session. We are simply looking for good groups with good songs to do some good recordings." Send a tape to Cornerstone Recording Studio, 8715 Rutledge Pike, Knoxville  37924.

<H3>TAPE O' THE MONTH</H3>
<STRONG>Beeswax
<BR>The Wrath and Fury of the Backslide Trash Heap Jive</STRONG>
<BR>Although they've been compared (with good intentions, to be sure) to Pavement repeatedly on these pages, Beeswax comes into their own and--for the most part--shrugs off the connection with The Wrath and Fury of the Backslide Trash Heap Jive (even more so now that they've added second guitarist Gray Comer). Sure, Todd Stapleton's vocals tend to be devil-may-care, and, yes, the guitars swagger as they stagger. But this is a band that has gone from being so lackadaisical they could've been a west coast bride to a sound that is at once low-slung and loose, yet never careless.
<P>Never mind saving the best for last; the band kicks in immediately with the air raid siren-gone-wrong guitar lash of "Anti-Acoustic Blues Groove in C", which settles into an infectious churn of rumbling noise while the whole thing plays out like a roller coaster ride. Along the way, the fantastic "Fodder" (with its stuttering, slit-eyed buzz of a groove), relentlessly hooky "As Iowa Slowly Shrinks," and ringing rush of "Thermal Bremmstrahlung" provide thrills, spills, highs, lows, jaw-rattling rhythms (courtesy of bassist Scott Heiskell and drummer Scott Henshaw), giddy speeds, screeching halts, until the bottom drops out from under you and slides home on a wave of ghostly noise called "Scapegoat."
<BR>Good to the last start-stop-start, and not a silly love song in the bunch.
<BR><STRONG>Beeswax play with String Joy at Gryphon's on Sat., Jan. 18; and State Champs at Gryphon's on Fri., Feb. 7.</STRONG>
<P><EM>Zippy "Despite all my other amazing powers, I am not omniscient--so quit bitching and make contact" McDuff</EM>

