<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>February 1 - February 29, 1996</H2>
<HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="605_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95" HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 5: February 1-8, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="605_ut.html">UT Meets the Millennium</A>
</H2><P>In the next five years, a large portion of <STRONG>UT's faculty and
administration</STRONG> will be reaching retirement age. This means new leaders
will be taking the helm of Tennessee's biggest university -- but who will
it be? <STRONG>Bill Dockery</STRONG> discovers that there are no heirs apparent.
<BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="606_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95" HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 6: February 8-15, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="606_ladyvols.html">The Spinderella Story</A>
</H2><P>What to do with a rogue "street ball" player in the highly disciplined
and technical basketball world of the Lady Vols? If the star point guard
in question weren't <STRONG>Michelle Marciniak, </STRONG>it would be just
another workaday surmountable challenge for Pat Head Summit, the head coach.
<STRONG>Brooks Clark</STRONG> explains why the personalities involved make
this player-coach relationship so successful -- and why they also prevent
it from being even more successful.
<BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="607_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95" HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 7: February 15-22, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="607_services.html">Desperately Seeking Services</A>
</H2><P>As newspaper headlines become crowded with stories of <STRONG>teen
criminals,</STRONG>
Gov. Sundquist has signed off on new policies for how Tennessee's troubled
kids are helped. What are these changes, and will the affect an already growing
problem? <STRONG>Janet Tate</STRONG> takes a look at how we deal with our
problem children.
<BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="608_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95" HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 8: February 22-29, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="608_downtown.html">Downtown Uplift</A>
</H2><P><STRONG>Joe Sullivan</STRONG> lends an ear to the meeting-meisters
who've gathered to put downtown Knoxville back on the map. While the
<STRONG>Next BIG
Steps</STRONG> plan -- brainstorming to do everything from attract tourists
to the World's Fair Park to revitalize downtown businesses -- seems worthy
of support, he notices that the biggest step has been overlooked. Who's going
to pay for it all?
<BR CLEAR=ALL><HR>

