<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>July 18 - August 15, 1996</H2>
<P><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="629_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95"  HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 29: July 18 - July 25, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="629_rescue.html">The Rescuers</A>
</H2><P><STRONG>Mike Gibson</STRONG> introduces members of the <STRONG>Knoxville Volunteer Rescue Squad</STRONG> -- the unsung heroes whose day's work is tending trauma and tragedy. Their time and attention is occupied almost constantly by training and preparing for what they hope will never happen, but too often does.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="630_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95"  HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 30: July 25 - August 1, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="630_justice.html">And Justice for All</A></H2>
<P><STRONG>Mike Gibson</STRONG> explains why Knoxville <EM>might</EM> gain a <STRONG>justice center</STRONG> -- a downtown mall occupied by courts, clerks, the attorney general's office, and all manner of law enforecement functionaries. Might, that is, pending the outcome of the political battles behind the proposal.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="631_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95"  HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 31: August 1 - August 8, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="631_stevesmith.html">Underdog</A></H2>
<P>For the past three decades, the Duncan family has held a seat representing Knoxvillians in the U.S. House of Representatives. And for the past three decades, Democratic challengers have stood down, writing a political battle off as a lost cause. Until now, that is. <STRONG>Bill Dockery</STRONG> reports on the campaign of local activist and  veterinarian <STRONG>Stephen Smith,</STRONG> an underdog David who can only hope one of his stones hits its mark on the political Goliath that is Rep. Jimmy Duncan.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="632_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95"  HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 32: August 8 - August 15, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="632_menu.html">Still Alive After Five</A></H2>
<P>Journey with us now through the arteries and veins and deep into the heart of Metro Pulse as we celebrate five years of sometimes precarious existence.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><HR>

