<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>November 7 - December 5, 1996</H2>
<P><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="645_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95"  HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 45: November 7 - November 14, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="645_gospel.html">Amazing Grace</A></H2>
Traditional <STRONG>gospel music</STRONG> has a strong history in Knoxville, but like all good things, gospel is changing with the times. While the choir and piano are giving way to pop-style singers and nouveau country combos, some of Knoxville's gospel cornerstones explain to <STRONG>Chris Barrett</STRONG> what lies ahead.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="646_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95"  HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 46: November 14 - November 21, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="646_inventors.html">Patent Pending</A></H2>
<STRONG>Mike Gibson</STRONG> introduces one of the few species in East Tennessee that's not endangered: the fanatical <STRONG>inventor.</STRONG> From high-tech to low-tech, rubber band-powered to solar-powered, some of the finest labor saving and decision-making widgets that the world currently enjoys started in Knoxville workshops, labs, and garages. Here's a peek at the people and what they currently have on the drawing boards.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="647_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95"  HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 47: November 21 - November 27, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="647_hunger.html">Hunger Strikes</A></H2>
While the appearance of the underfed, undernourished Knoxvillian remains a far cry from the vintage news file photos of "Third World" Appalachia, all swollen tummies and sunken eyes, there is an ever-increasing number of <STRONG>hungry people</STRONG> in our community. <STRONG>Katie Allison Granju</STRONG> introduces some neighbors who either barely or don't subsist on assistance programs like food stamps, and asks some area program administrators what the needy and the rest of us have to look forward to.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><HR>

<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="648_thumb.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="95"  HSPACE="10">
<STRONG>Volume 6, Number 48: November 27 - December 5, 1996</STRONG>
<H2><A HREF="648_bankruptcy.html">Drowning in Debt</A></H2>
Even with its restrictive legislation aimed at averting such plagues, Tennessee leads the nation in <STRONG>personal bankruptcies</STRONG> - and East Tennessee is contributing its share to that lead. While interviewing debtors, attorneys, and personal finance experts, <STRONG>Val Pendergrast</STRONG> finds that job loss, susceptibility to credit advertising, and "keeping up with the Joneses" all play a part in East Tennessee's ongoing bankruptcy epidemic.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT><HR>

</BODY></HTML>
