<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Clubs &amp; Venues</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000"><P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="../../index.shtml"><IMG ALIGN=Middle  SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_home.gif" ALT="Front Page" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../zine.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle  SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_zine.gif" ALT="The 'Zine" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../suncity.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle  SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_suncity.gif" ALT="Sunsphere City" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../market.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle  SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_market.gif" ALT=" Marketplace" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../bonus.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle  SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_bonus.gif" ALT="Bonus Track" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="head_venues.gif" ALT="Knoxville bars, venues, and so forth" WIDTH="411" HEIGHT="36"><BR><A HREF="../calendar_dir/calendar.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_calendar.gif" ALT="Entertainment Calendar" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="2" VSPACE="3"></A><A HREF="../band_dir/menu_local.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_band_local.gif" ALT="Local Bands" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="2"  VSPACE="3"></A>
<P>Please find enclosed a selected assortment of Knoxville's delightful bars,
clubs, concert venues, and so forth. Thank you.
<P ALIGN=CENTER><STRONG>CLUBS: [ </STRONG><A HREF="#rock">Rock</A> |
<A HREF="#honkytonks">Honky
Tonks</A> |
<A HREF="#dance">Dance</A> | <A HREF="#jazzblues">Jazz and Blues</A> |
<A HREF="#neighborhood">Neighborhood Bars</A> <STRONG>]</STRONG>
<BR><STRONG><A HREF="#venues">THEATERS &amp; ARENAS</A> |
<A HREF="#tickets">TICKET INFO</A></STRONG>
<P><HR><A NAME=rock><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="hed_rock.gif" ALT="Rock Clubs" WIDTH="98" HEIGHT="26"></A>

<H2>Mercury Theatre </H2>
<STRONG>28 Market Square (downtown Knoxville) / (423) 637-8634</STRONG>
<BR>Open Tues. - Sun., with dance nights every Tues. and Sun. night.
<BR>Mercury Theatre hosts alternative bands the likes of Jon Spencer Blues Explosion, Royal Trux, Archers of Loaf, Jawbox and Jonathan Fire*eater, as well as a plethora of local bands.
<BR>Evolving decor of outer space, wild west and skate punk themes. Decent beer prices and selection, reasonable covers. The bar area, including foosball tables, tends to be a "seen and be seen" hangout for local music luminaries. Dance night Sundays. Live rap with DJ Smooth Tuesdays. Parking is usually not a problem, since the huge lot behind the other side of Market Square is yours for the taking at night. Restrooms lack something to be desired, especially as the night runs on and the toilet paper runs out. Capacity 200.

<H2>Flamingo's</H2>
<STRONG>1836 Cumberland Ave. (on the Strip) / (423) 546-2323</STRONG>
<BR>Located in the heart of the campus of the University of Tennessee, Flamingo's stage features plenty of neo-hippie grooves and straight-forward Southern rock, as well as a smattering of commercial alternative bands (Letters To Cleo, Son Volt).
<BR>Flamingo's is not the most inviting or cozy room by any stretch of the imagination, but it serves its purpose with a capacity of 500. This is where you'll find the Spin Doctors/Dave Matthews Band/et al before they hit the big time. A real pitcher-of-beer kind of place; restaurant/deli/foosball tables downstairs. Restrooms acceptable. Parking a hassle. Located on the Strip, Flamingo's has about 3 parking spaces of its own in front; bank lot next door is usable, though. Otherwise, you've gotta scout out the Lake Avenue area.

<H2>Amigo's</H2>
<STRONG>116 S. Central Ave. (in the Old City) / (423) 546-9505</STRONG>
<BR>Blues, acoustic and a little bit of rock 'n' roll fit the bill at Amigo's, a Mexican restaurant and bar all wrapped up in one. Music every weekend, and upstairs performances (usually acoustic) are often free. Amigo's is also home to Knoxville's annual El Vez show, an event not to be missed.
<P>Nice restrooms; Typical Old City parking-- fend for yourself. Capacity 220, including restaurant.

<H2>Bombay Bicycle Club</H2>
<STRONG>6300 Papermill Rd. / (423) 584-0544</STRONG>
<BR>Dance nights Wed., Fri., and Sat. at 5pm, Sun. at 7.
<BR>Besides featuring popular dance nights, Bombay Bicycle Club is the place to see tribute bands of every shape and size, from Strutter (KISS) to Cowboys From Hell (Pantera), Heart-Shaped Box (Nirvana) to Downward Spiral (Nine Inch Nails, White Zombie and Rage Against the Machine). A new tribute every Thursday and occasional appearances by 70's rockers down on their luck. Plenty of bars, above average restrooms. Unfortunately, there are very few good vantage points, and, although there are parking lots on all sides of the building, they're often full. Capacity 500.

<H2>The Library</H2>
<STRONG>1910 Cumberland Ave. / (423) 546-0066</STRONG>
<BR>Straight-ahead, red-blooded rock 'n' roll is the call of the wild at The Library, located on the University of Tennessee campus. Music most every weekend, usually a mix of local and out-of-town bands. Bathrooms are acceptable. Capacity of 400 or so. No onsite parking; fend for yourself on the streets behind the club.

<P><HR><A NAME=honkytonks><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="hed_tonks.gif" ALT="Honky Tonks" WIDTH="110" HEIGHT="26"></A>

<H2>Judy's II</H2>
<STRONG>5916 Middlebrook Pike / (423) 584-3837</STRONG>
<BR>Country music is what you'll find at Judy's II, where it's non-stop
honky-tonk seven days a week. Capacity 150.

<H2>Cotton-Eyed Joe</H2>
<STRONG>11220 Outlet Dr. / (423) 675-4563</STRONG>
<BR>If boot-scootin' boogie is your thing, you'll want to check out
Cotton-Eyed Joe. Besides being Knoxville's line-dancing headquarters (30,000
square feet of dancing room) every single night of the week, Cotton-Eyed
Joe also features big-name live performances from the likes of George Jones
and Confederate Railroad. Lessons begin at 7 pm.

<H2>David's Music Barn</H2>
<STRONG>8625 Clinton Hwy. / (423) 945-3595</STRONG>
<BR>Located just outside the Knoxville city limits, David's Music Barn
is the place for colorful, downhome bluegrass.

<P><HR><A NAME=dance><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="hed_dance.gif" ALT="Dance Clubs" WIDTH="108" HEIGHT="26"></A>

<H2>The Carousel</H2>
<STRONG>1501 White Ave / (423) 522-6966</STRONG>
<BR>Disco and drag, Wed., Fri., Sat. and Sun. beginning 9pm.

<H2>Lord Lindsey</H2>
<STRONG>W. Hill Ave. / (423) 522-2178</STRONG>
<BR>Shake it, baby, shake it, at The Closet, Lord Lindsey's weekly dance
adventure, as DJs spin the latest and greatest in underground grooves. Every
Thursday beginning 11 pm.

<H2>Michael's</H2>
<STRONG>7049 Kingston Pike / (423) 588-2455</STRONG>
<BR>Top 40 and baby boomers mix and mingle at Michael's every night
of the week. Sunday means "oldies."

<H2>Trump's</H2>
<STRONG>4541 Kingston Pike / (423) 584-4884</STRONG>
<BR>Definitely off the beaten path, Trump's features a high-energy dance
atmosphere and drag shows Mon-Sat. evenings.

<H2>Underground/Boiler Room</H2>
<STRONG>214 W. Jackson Ave / (423) 525-3675</STRONG>
<BR>The big daddy of dance, the Underground is a mulit-layered, cavernous
experience unto itself. An eclectic mix of Top 40 and techno is the specialty
of the house, known to be packed beyond breathing room most every weekend.
Truly underground, the Boiler Room is gonna make you sweat to the latest
in alternative dance beats, Fri. and Sat. 1 - 6am. The Underground fun begins
at 10 pm Mon., Wed., Fri. and Sat.

<H2>The Frog Pad</H2>
<STRONG>131 S. Central St. / (423) 971-3030</STRONG>
<BR>Dancehall and reggae raise the roof at The Frog Pad in the Old City, Tuesday is alternative night, Thursday is blues and bluegrass, and DJs spinning the latest Carib sounds every Wednesday. Capacity 180.

<H2>Sound Factory</H2>
<STRONG>125 E. Jackson Ave. 546-8500</STRONG>
<BR>Shake your groove thing, boys. Friday and Saturday beginning 10pm.

<P><HR><A NAME=jazzblues><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="hed_jazzblues.gif" ALT="Jazz and Blues" WIDTH="115" HEIGHT="26"></A>

<H2>Lucille's</H2>
<STRONG>106 S. Central St. (in the Old City) / (423) 546-3742</STRONG>
<BR>Lucille's, Knoxville's jazz mecca, is currently closed, but may reopen soon. We certainly hope so, anyway.

<H2>Ivory's</H2>
<STRONG>4715 Old Kingston Pike. (423) 588-6023.</STRONG>
<BR>318 N. Gay St. 423-637-9805More than just a piano bar, Ivory's lets local musicians sing the blues and more, .Mon. and Wed. - Sat.

<H2>Regas--The Gathering Place</H2>
<STRONG>318 N. Gay St. (423) 637-9805</STRONG>
<BR>A well-loved institution of a restaurant by day (recently voted the TK-best in the South by Southern Living magazine readers), Regas's bar turns into a hip little cabaret in the evening (Wed.-Sat.).

<P><HR><A NAME=neighborhood><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="hed_neighborhood.gif" ALT="Neighborhood Bars" WIDTH="171" HEIGHT="26"></A>

<H2>Sassy Ann's</H2>
<STRONG>820 N. Fourth Ave. / (423) 525-5839</STRONG>
<BR>Housed in a vintage Victorian in Knoxville's historic 4th and Gill
district, Sassy Ann's is a cozy restaurant and bar which just happens to
feature live blues six nights a week. A songwriter's night and open mic is
held every Sunday evening, with an open jam on Wednesdays. Capacity 80+.

<H2>Dante's</H2>
<STRONG>1801 Lake Ave. (One block behind Cumberland Ave.) (423) 525-3268</STRONG>
<BR>Dante's hosts bands both on the outside deck and by the bar.  Music goes from jazz/funk styles to neo-hippy. Covers are no more than $2. Extensive beer selection includes microbrews on tap and 75 imports. Food selections such as burgers, pizza and calzones. Capacity 150. 

<H2>Gryphon's</H2>
<STRONG>2003 Highland Ave. / (423) 524-6996</STRONG>
<BR>A combination
bar and laundromat, Gryphon's is open 24 hours, 7
days a week, and you can find just about any and everything here, from punk
to blues to acoustic folk. Lots of local bands get their start here, and
music is often free. Not for the faint of heart.

<H2>Hoo-Ray's</H2>
<BR><STRONG>106 S. Central St. / (423) 546-6729</STRONG><BR>Hoo-Ray's
is a larger-than-life sports bar extraordinaire located
in the heart of the historic Old City. Capacity 700.

<H2>Amsterdam Cafe</H2>
<STRONG>102 S. Central St. / (423) 523-2437</STRONG>
<BR>Small but cozy, Amsterdam Cafe is a bar with an
incredible beer selection in the Old City. Word of mouth, and foosball tables,
have made it a popular Gen-X hangout. You can find acoustic and plugged-in
rock and blues on the weekends and, sometimes, during the week, as well.

<H2>Hawkeye's</H2>
<STRONG>1717 White Ave. (423) 524-5326</STRONG>
<BR>A favorite of UT students and grads alike, Hawkeye's serves up American fare in a warm and inviting old house in Fort Sanders. Live music takes over upstairs Thurs.-Sat., making the already-packed bar a shoulder-to-shoulder affair. The real draw, though, is Animal Hour, an infamous and nightly 2-for-1 liquor happy hour.

<P><HR><A NAME=venues><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="hed_arenas.gif" ALT="Theaters & Arenas" WIDTH="167" HEIGHT="26"></A>

<H2>Bijou Theatre</H2>
<STRONG>803 S. Gay St. / (423) 522-0832</STRONG>
<BR>Capacity: 750
seats. Onsite box office
open 10 a.m. - 5 p.m., weekdays,
and before events.

<H2>Electric Ballroom International</H2>
<STRONG>1213 Western Ave / (423) 525-6724</STRONG>
<BR>Capacity 1,250.
Onsite box office
open before events.

<H2>Knoxville Civic Auditorium</H2>
<STRONG>500 E. Church Ave. / (423) 544-5388</STRONG>
<BR>Capacity
2,410 seats. Onsite
box office open and 10 a.m. - 5 p.m., weekdays,
and before events.

<H2>Knoxville Civic Coliseum</H2>
<STRONG>500 E. Church Ave. / (423) 544-5388</STRONG>
<BR>Capacity 4,414 seats. Onsite box office open 10 a.m. - 5 p.m., weekdays,
and before events.

<H2>Laurel Theatre</H2>
<STRONG>1538 Laurel Ave. / (423) 522-5851</STRONG>
<BR>Capacity 220.

<H2>Tennessee Theatre</H2>
<STRONG>604 S. Gay St. / (423) 522-1174</STRONG>
<BR>Capacity 1,548
seats. Onsite box office open before events. Truly beautiful theater.

<H2>Thompson-Boling Arena</H2>
<STRONG>1600 Stadium Dr.,
University of Tennessee campus / (423) 656-4444</STRONG>
<BR>Capacity 24,535.
Tickets Unlimited box office onsite is
open 8:30 a.m.
- 4:30 p.m., weekdays, and before Arena events.

<P><HR><A NAME=tickets><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="hed_tickets.gif" ALT="Ticket Information" WIDTH="93" HEIGHT="26"></A>
<P>Several venues sell tickets through <A HREF="http://www.wtwcom.com/tickets">Tickets Unlimited</A>: 423-656-4444.
The Tickets Unlimited box office, located in Thompson-Boling Arena, is open
8:30 a.m. - 4:30 p.m. weekdays. Phone hours are 8 a.m. - 7 p.m.
<UL><P><STRONG>Tickets Unlimited outlets include:</STRONG>
<LI>Disc Exchange, 2615 Chapman Hwy. 423-573-5710
<LI>Disc Exchange, 8420 Kingston Pike. 423-470-0120
<LI>Cat's Compact Discs and Cassettes, 7337 Kingston Pike. 423-588-2287
<LI>Cat's Compact Discs and Cassettes, 1707 Cumberland Ave. 423-521-7500
<LI>Proffitt's department store, West Town Mall. 423-694-0094
<LI>Proffitt's department store, East Towne Mall. 423-637-2117
</UL><P><HR>
</BODY></HTML>
