<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Metro Pulse Calendar Spotlights</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000">
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="../../index.shtml"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_home.gif" ALT="Front Page" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../zine.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_zine.gif" ALT="The 'Zine" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../suncity.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_suncity.gif" ALT="Sunsphere City" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../market.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_market.gif" ALT=" Marketplace" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<A HREF="../../bonus.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_bonus.gif" ALT="Bonus Track" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1"></A>
<P ALIGN=Center>
<IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="hed_spotlights.gif" ALT="Metro Pulse Calendar Spotlights" WIDTH="300" HEIGHT="27"><BR>
<A HREF="../calendar_dir/calendar.html"><IMG ALIGN=Middle SRC="../../graphics_misc/b_calendar.gif" ALT="Calendar" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="14" HSPACE="1" VSPACE="3"></A>

<H2>1964</H2>
Unlike Oasis, this starry-eyed imitation of (and tribute to) the Fab Four cops not just the sound, but the boots and the suits and the haircuts, too. See Paul bob his head like he has a coiled spring for a throat, watch as Ringo shakes his shaggy hair out of his eyes, squint to see if this John can come up with anything even close to Lennon's wicked grin. And then there are the fans, attempting to re-create the hysteria with their squeals and gasps (no, really). Of course, the fact that the band's name is 1964 pretty much limits their repertoire, but anyone who enjoyed Backbeat should at least get a kick out of this dedicated and well-planned homage.
<STRONG><BR>1964
<BR>Tennessee Theatre, Sat., Jan. 11, 8 p.m., $15, 656-4444</STRONG>

<H2>J.D. CROWE AND THE NEW SOUTH</H2>
True blue (grass, that is) fans know well the three-decade history of revered banjo-picker J.D. Crowe, from his early days with Jimmy Martin in the '50s right on up to fronting the New South--an outfit that has proved a star-studded stepping stone for the likes of Tony Rice, Ricky Skaggs, Jerry Douglas, and Keith Whitley. They know his incredible discography (J.D. Crowe &amp; the New South, Live In Japan, and 1994's ebullient retrospective Flashback, to name a few). They mourned his temporary retirement that stretched from the late '80s to 1994, and they said hallelujah when he finally returned to his five-string--along with East Tennessean Phil Leadbetter on dobro and the fantastic Richard Bennett on vocals. And now they've got even more reason to crack a great big smile, as J.D. Crowe and the New South return to the Bijou Theatre with their sound that is at once contemporary and traditional--and, simply said, bluegrass at its best.
<STRONG><BR>J.D. Crowe &amp; the New South w/IIIrd Tyme Out
<BR>Bijou Theatre, Sat., Jan. 11, 7:30 p.m., $15, 656-4444</STRONG>

<H2>KING WEEK</H2>
In the spirit of the man which it honors, King Week is more than just a celebratory remembrance, but also--and perhaps most importantly--an opportunity for educational growth. The Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., Commemoration kicks off with the annual Leadership Symposium, Thursday, Jan. 16, 9 a.m. at the Radisson Hotel. Guest speaker is Deborah Mathis, nationally syndicated columnist and White House correspondent for Gannet News Service. This will be followed by a Labor, Government, Business, and Industry Awards Luncheon; tickets are $30. The next generation steps up with a youth symposium on Saturday at Austin-East High School, 9 a.m. Finally, a celebration service takes place Sun., beginning with a parade at 4:30 p.m. at Tabernacle Baptist Church (2137 M.L.K. Ave.). The parade route winds up at Greater Warner Tabernacle AME Zion Church, where Rev. Dr. Benjamin Hooks, former Executive Director of the NAACP, will speak at 6 p.m.
<STRONG><BR>King Week
<BR>Thurs., Jan. 16-Sun., Jan. 19. 524-2482</STRONG>
<P>
<EM>--Shelly Ridenour</EM> 
